                    h4 Who, Where, When
                    h6 Primary User
                    p The photographer's clients — people who hired a photographer for portraits, events, or commercial work and need to select which images they want retouched. They have no photography background and varying technical comfort. The tool must work fluently for the least technical person in the room, on whatever device they pick up. No tutorial. No account. Just a link that works.
                    h6 Secondary User
                    p The photographer. Every minute a client spends sending back-and-forth emails is time spent managing communication instead of editing. The tool needs to get clients to a confident, exportable selection without hand-holding.
                    h6 Where &amp; When
                    p Hosted on the photographer's own website. Clients receive a link via email after a shoot, when proof images are delivered, and review 100+ photos in a single session at their own pace — on desktop or mobile, with no friction before they can start.

                    h4(data-title="Solutions") What
                    h6 How do we prioritize?
                    p Features were divided into phases by what would most reduce client hesitation and back-and-forth communication. The build moved through 5 phases in 2 days. Because I was prototyping directly in the browser with Claude AI rather than designing in Figma and waiting on a development handoff I was able to explore flows more more completely even with multiple non-linear application states.

