                    h4(data-title="Process") Process — AI-Assisted Prototyping &amp; Build
                    h6 Why I prototyped in the browser instead of Figma
                    p This project called for a different process. The interface has three interconnected views sharing live state — the kind of nonlinear, stateful interactions that look fine in a Figma prototype and break immediately in a real browser. Rather than designing static flows and writing specs for a developer to interpret, <strong>I used Claude AI to prototype directly in the browser</strong> — describing design intent in plain language and iterating on working code in real time. Complex state problems got caught during design, not QA. The result was a 2-day path from concept to shipped production tool.

                    .info-box
                        h6 The core advantage over a Figma handoff
                        p The traditional pipeline creates a gap between design intent and built reality — especially for nonlinear, stateful interfaces. You can design a happy path beautifully and still not hit interaction failures until a developer has already built it. With Claude, I was testing <strong>real state interactions from the very first iteration</strong>, not static mockups. The feedback loop collapsed from days to minutes.

                    h6 State problems caught during live prototyping
                    p This interface has three interconnected views — the main gallery grid, the single-image lightbox, and compare mode — all sharing the same state. These problems only surface when testing live interactions, not reviewing a Figma file:

                    .state-list
                        .sp
                            p.sp-title Selection + rating sync across all views
                            p Rating an image in the compare lightbox needed to update simultaneously in the main grid, the lightbox header, and the active filter view — without a page refresh. Invisible in a Figma prototype. Immediately testable in a live Claude prototype.
                        .sp
                            p.sp-title Filter reactivity to live rating changes
                            p The star filter had to react to live rating changes — downrate an image below the threshold and it disappears from the filtered view instantly, even inside the lightbox or compare mode. One iteration to discover and resolve because we tested real state transitions.
                        .sp
                            p.sp-title Zoom &amp; pan state per-image in compare mode
                            p Each of up to 5 compare panels needed its own independent zoom and pan state — zooming one panel couldn't affect the others. This isolation requirement only became clear once tested live in the browser.

                    .wf
                        .wf-col
                            p.wf-head Traditional Figma → Handoff
                            ul.wf-steps
                                li Design happy-path flows in Figma
                                li Write interaction specs for stateful edge cases
                                li Hand off to developer
                                li Developer builds v1
                                li QA reveals cross-view state bugs
                                li Revise specs, schedule fixes
                                li Multi-week cycle to shipped product
                        .wf-col.new
                            p.wf-head Vibe Coding with Claude AI
                            ul.wf-steps
                                li Describe design intent in plain language
                                li.hl Claude generates working browser prototype
                                li.hl Test real state interactions immediately
                                li.hl Catch cross-view bugs during design, not QA
                                li Refine and iterate in the same session
                                li Ship production-ready code directly
                                li.hl 2 days, concept to live tool

                    h3(data-title="Validation") How
                    p How did I measure impact and growth to validate the solution?

                    h6 User
                    ul
                        li Clients needed no instructions — they opened a link and started rating without any guidance, which is the clearest signal a client-facing tool can give you
                        li Multiple clients described the selection process as feeling easy
                        li Clients purchased additional upsells

                    h6 Community validation
                    ul
                        li Other photographers in the community said multi-image compare was something they'd wanted for years — confirming the gap wasn't unique to my studio
                        li Unsolicited purchase interest from multiple photographers before any marketing or distribution effort

                    h6 Next
                    ul
                        li Stable distributable release for non-developer photographers
                        li Optional client commenting
                        li Streamlined setup experience

